observations.recommendation:
a. Review its duly constituted Inventory Committee. Tap more people to do the physical count and set schedule with the various departments/offices to ensure that complete physical inventory-taking be made. Assign one person in each department/office who will maintain the records of all property, plant, and equipment issued to the concerned officers and employees to ensure timely and complete Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, & Equipment (RPCPPE);
b. Reconcile annually the RPCPPE with the accounting records and investigate discrepancies noted for its proper valuation in the FS;
c. Strictly implement the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances, draw necessary accounting entries, measurements, presentation and disclosure requirements as provided in the COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
d. Through the GSO, observe the necessary protocols in the disposal of unserviceable properties;
e. Allocate budget for premium insurance and direct the General Services Office to prepare and accomplish the Property Insurance Form (PIF) for uninsured properties. Insure against any insurable risk the properties, assets, and interests with the GIF, as administered by the GSIS the soonest possible time to protect agency assets against losses due to fire, earthquake and other calamities; and
f. Allocate in the annual budget of the Municipality, the estimated cost for titling of land and create a committee or team that will focus on expediting titling of all lots/land acquired and for prospective acquisitions thereof to protect its interests from possible third-party claims.

a. The LGU has not yet established a Data-base System to serve as information repositories for performance-based and gender-responsive planning and budgeting;
b. Make operational and available anytime the GAD Database for easy monitoring of GAD projects.
c. Set the GAD agenda or identify priority gender issues and/or specific GAD mandates and targets to be addressed over a one-year or three-year term of the Local Chief Executive (LCE) and ensure provision of adequate resources (including personnel);
d. May consider consulting with local stakeholders for better formulation of PPAs to be included in the GPB, and proposal of training programs to toughen GFPS in GAD-related concerns and outcomes;
e. Revisit the Philippine Plan for Gender-Responsive Development 1995-2025 which cites programs under different sectors like human development, economic and industrial, infrastructure and technology, and special concerns sector that will help in achieving the Sustainable Development Goals or Agenda 2030; and
f. Properly monitor implementation of GAD programs/projects/activities of the agency to ensure efficiency in managing its resources and effective observance of its CY 2020 objectives; and
g. Adopt the GAD-Plan and Budget Monitoring System developed by the DILG for ease in submission of GAD Plan and Budget, and Accomplishment Report as well as receive timely feedbacks for need of updating reports, as applicable.

a. Thoroughly review all the documents attached and ensure compliance with the requirements for emergency purchase as embodied in R.A. 11469 of the Bayanihan to Heal as One Act, including certifying as to completeness of the supporting documents to the related Disbursement Vouchers (DVs);
b. Promptly submit copies of the contract and purchase orders including all its supporting documents within the prescribed timeline in consonance to COA Circular 2009-001 for review and evaluation of the subject programs, projects and activities (PPAs);
c. Comply with the posting and reporting requirements of the GPPB Circular 01-2020 and DBM LBC No. 125.

a. Identify specific projects, programs and activities (PPAs) with timelines to be integrated in Annual Investment Program to maximize the benefits to be derived therefrom. Revisit the NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013 and other pertinent guidelines to encompass the four (4) thematic areas of DRRM such as disaster prevention and mitigation, disaster preparedness, disaster response, and disaster rehabilitation and recovery;
b. Efficiently utilize the fund for the purpose designed such as accelerating the procurement of the needed disaster and rescue equipment to improve the capacity of the Municipality to respond in emergencies or disasters, obtaining the necessary documents pertaining to the lot acquired to proceed with land development, and the acquisition of lots for the eight (8) remaining barangays;
c. Re-evaluate the PPAs for which the funds were originally set out for but remain unimplemented as of date in congruence with the pressing needs of the community;
d. DRRMO and the related LGU Officials and employees strictly comply with the accounting and reporting requirements embodied in R.A. 10121 and COA Circular 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012 and COA Circular 2014-002 dated April 15, 2014 to ensure that the financial information is appropriately taken up in the books with adequate disclosures. The same reports should have been posted in the LGU’s website and full disclosure portal of the DILG; and
e. DRRMO provide other related reports that may be requested throughout the audit process in an expeditious manner.

a. Coordinate with the Local Development Council and Local Finance Committee and promote/encourage optimum utilization of the 20% Economic Development Fund by adhering on-going guidelines like the DILG-DBM JMC 2017-01;
b. Consider creating a specific committee/team that will spearhead the planning and evaluation of PPAs’ feasibility. Devise a suitable “Project Identification Process” as course or roadmap in utilizing the fund. Factors such as priority needs, location, resources available (duration and manpower) be taken into account;
c. Re-evaluation of implementation feasibility for PPAs not yet started, including those of the prior years’ appropriation;
d. Streamline all other procedures necessary to be undertaken for the PPAs to be materialized and evaluated.

a. Comply with the minimum requirements set by Section 12 of RA 9003 on the creation of Municipal Solid Waste Management Board (MSWMB);
b. Intensify its efforts to have the existing Solid Waste Management Plan (SWMP) for 2017-2027 approved by the National Solid Waste Management Commission (NSWMC) to be in line with the vision of preserving the natural resources of the Municipality;
c. Devise local ordinances and strictly enforce implementation of the provisions of Sections 21 and 22 of RA 9003 on the mandatory segregation of solid wastes and carry out the following: Strengthen Information and Education Campaign activities by using the LGU website or social media to promote awareness and encourage participation from the community in managing solid wastes; Establish close coordination with barangay officials to ensure that efforts to improve the SWM will reach the constituents at the barangay level; and Impose fines and penalties for any offense made or in violation of Section 48 of RA 9003; and
d. Prioritize the closure of the open dump, construct and operate a sanitary landfill as a final disposal site for solid wastes pursuant to the criteria set in Section 40 of RA 9003 to ensure protection of public health and the environment.

a. Provide adequate support and funding for the construction of necessary facilities and speed up the provision of water supply;
b. Partner with National Meat Inspection Commission (NMIC) being the agency assigned for the training and accreditation of personnel on slaughterhouse operation;
c. Formulate, adopt and implement specific rules and regulations to ensure efficiency, effectiveness, order and viable operations of the slaughterhouse to serve as additional source of income that will help in the LGU in providing other services to the public.
